00:02:08.110 --> 00:02:11.660
And let's start with that
simple capacity analysis.

00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:14.500
So this is a
theoretical exercise,

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:18.130
but it gives you some idea
of how one might approach--

00:02:18.130 --> 00:02:20.400
if you have nothing
to go on, how

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:23.730
one might approach
estimating what capacity

00:02:23.730 --> 00:02:25.380
you need for some service.

00:02:25.380 --> 00:02:29.460
So the problem is, given
a pie-shaped sector

00:02:29.460 --> 00:02:31.650
into the central
business district served

00:02:31.650 --> 00:02:34.830
by a single transit line, what
will be the peak passenger

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:37.800
flow entering the central
business district.

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:40.110
And that might give you an
idea of what mode you need.

00:02:40.110 --> 00:02:40.609
Right?

00:02:40.609 --> 00:02:41.990
Can you run a bus system?

00:02:41.990 --> 00:02:46.350
Do you need a light rail,
a BRT, a heavy rail?

00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:48.870
So it gives you some idea.

00:02:48.870 --> 00:02:50.790
And you might have
some statistics

00:02:50.790 --> 00:02:53.220
about the city where
you're being asked about,

00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:54.390
the question.

00:02:54.390 --> 00:02:56.100
And so you can make
some assumptions.

00:02:56.100 --> 00:02:59.920
You can draw this on the back
of a napkin and, you know,

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:02.820
do some calculus with
it if you want to.

00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:04.630
And that's what
we're going to do.

00:03:04.630 --> 00:03:07.220
So I'm going to draw on
the board a little bit.

00:03:14.180 --> 00:03:16.770
What do we have here?

00:03:16.770 --> 00:03:22.960
Yeah, I'll draw the same
shape here for reference.

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:28.760
So we have a cone-shaped
sector or a pie-shaped sector.

00:03:28.760 --> 00:03:33.230
And there's some angle
of that corridor, which

00:03:33.230 --> 00:03:36.560
is the catchment area
over which people

00:03:36.560 --> 00:03:38.150
might walk to the service.

00:03:38.150 --> 00:03:41.780
The service, by the
way, is along some line,

00:03:41.780 --> 00:03:49.290
and it reaches the city center,
which we're calling the CBD.

00:03:49.290 --> 00:03:52.950
And at that center, there is
some density, some population

00:03:52.950 --> 00:03:59.460
density, which we call
P sub c, the population

00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:02.340
density at the center.

00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:10.040
And at any point along this
pie or pie-shaped sector,

00:04:10.040 --> 00:04:16.220
this, the length of
this arc, is r theta,

00:04:16.220 --> 00:04:24.110
where theta is the angle, and
r is the radius from the CBD

00:04:24.110 --> 00:04:28.200
up to that point.

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:30.240
So r is a variable,
and it starts at 0,

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:32.520
and it extends all the
way up to the length

00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:36.580
of the corridor,
which is L. L is

00:04:36.580 --> 00:04:40.370
the maximum value r can take.

00:04:40.370 --> 00:04:42.750
Does that make sense?

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:44.282
Everybody following?

00:04:44.282 --> 00:04:50.750
OK, and then we take little
slices of these arcs.

00:04:50.750 --> 00:04:59.600
And they have a very, very thin,
infinitesimally small width,

00:04:59.600 --> 00:05:07.890
dr. And we can--

00:05:07.890 --> 00:05:11.310
that sort of sets the stage
for what we want to do here.

00:05:11.310 --> 00:05:12.360
Let's assume something.

00:05:12.360 --> 00:05:16.110
Let's start assuming the
population density, which

00:05:16.110 --> 00:05:21.030
starts at a very high level
in the center of the business

00:05:21.030 --> 00:05:23.772
district, starts
dropping as you move out.

00:05:23.772 --> 00:05:24.480
That makes sense.

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:24.690
Right?

00:05:24.690 --> 00:05:26.320
In most cities,
that's what happens.

00:05:26.320 --> 00:05:28.580
We're going to assume
that it drops linearly

00:05:28.580 --> 00:05:33.960
and that it reaches some value
lower than Pc at some distance

00:05:33.960 --> 00:05:35.430
L from the CBD.

00:05:35.430 --> 00:05:43.060
And if we look at the
distance from the CBD

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:52.550
here, which we call r, and we
start at 0, 0 is at the CBD.

00:05:52.550 --> 00:05:53.840
Right?

00:05:53.840 --> 00:05:58.150
We start with a
population density of Pc.

00:05:58.150 --> 00:06:01.940
And we're going to assume it
drops linearly to some amount.

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:05.330
And at some point,
we'll reach L.

00:06:05.330 --> 00:06:07.400
And that's where we
stop the corridor.

00:06:07.400 --> 00:06:14.460
So this part doesn't really
matter because the corridor

00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:17.310
doesn't serve the part.

00:06:17.310 --> 00:06:23.790
And the rate at which that
population density declines,

00:06:23.790 --> 00:06:34.200
we will call delta P.
OK, so total population

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:37.240
density is decreasing as we
move outwards from the center.

00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:39.900
All right, so let's
start with what is

00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:41.820
the population in the corridor.

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:42.320
Right?

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:46.020
Because we need to know how many
people are in that corridor.

00:06:46.020 --> 00:06:48.330
And then from that,
we can calculate,

00:06:48.330 --> 00:06:50.160
based on some assumptions,
how many people

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:51.750
might access that line.

00:06:54.655 --> 00:06:57.850
So we'll start with
calculating the population

00:06:57.850 --> 00:07:00.250
in that whole pie-shaped sector.

00:07:00.250 --> 00:07:07.190
All right, so call
it population.

00:07:07.190 --> 00:07:13.060
So we'll take an integral from
r equals 0 to r equals L, which

00:07:13.060 --> 00:07:14.320
is the length of the corridor.

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:26.720
And we take r theta, which is
the length of this arc, which

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:29.920
it starts very small and gets
longer and longer until we

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:36.260
get to this part,
which is L theta alone.

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:36.760
Right?

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:38.520
So this is the arc length.

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:53.620
And we multiply by the
arc width, which is dr.

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:56.620
And we multiply by the
population density.

00:07:56.620 --> 00:07:58.840
And the population
density is a function

00:07:58.840 --> 00:08:00.330
of how far we are
from the center.

00:08:00.330 --> 00:08:05.380
So that's going to be P of r.

00:08:05.380 --> 00:08:09.860
And we can call
this graph P of r.

00:08:12.910 --> 00:08:14.320
The y value here is P of r.

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:16.330
It starts at Pc, drops to 0.

00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:20.890
Or before reaching--
well, yeah, it

00:08:20.890 --> 00:08:24.010
doesn't get to 0 at the
point of reaching L. Right?

00:08:24.010 --> 00:08:26.230
So it remains positive
throughout the length

00:08:26.230 --> 00:08:28.810
of the corridor.

00:08:28.810 --> 00:08:32.200
All right, and now we can
just, you know, do some math

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:35.169
and calculate this.

00:08:35.169 --> 00:08:40.970
So I'll just run through it.

00:08:40.970 --> 00:08:47.350
So we have r theta dr. Let's
substitute this function, which

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:49.000
is the population density.

00:08:53.630 --> 00:08:55.610
We assume that it
had this shape.

00:08:55.610 --> 00:08:59.010
So let's plug that in here.

00:08:59.010 --> 00:09:00.430
It's a linear function.

00:09:00.430 --> 00:09:03.570
So it starts at the
center with a high number,

00:09:03.570 --> 00:09:12.771
and it decreases as a function
of r at a rate of dP and times

00:09:12.771 --> 00:09:13.270
r.

00:09:13.270 --> 00:09:13.769
Right?

00:09:13.769 --> 00:09:17.180
So when r equals 0,
there's no decrease.

00:09:17.180 --> 00:09:20.150
As you move this way,
you multiply r times dP,

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:22.940
and you get the
difference between Pc

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:26.240
and the point where you are.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:42.370
All right, here I'm just
going to collect terms to make

00:09:42.370 --> 00:09:43.810
things look a little nicer.

00:10:02.310 --> 00:10:07.250
All right, so again, we're just
distributing this times that

00:10:07.250 --> 00:10:08.250
and that times that.

00:10:08.250 --> 00:10:10.130
So we have now two integrals.

00:10:13.010 --> 00:10:15.170
We can take some constants out.

00:10:15.170 --> 00:10:18.862
So theta is a constant,
and Pc is a constant.

00:10:18.862 --> 00:10:20.570
So we can take those
out of the integral.

00:10:24.660 --> 00:10:28.560
And we continue
integrating from 0 to L.

00:10:28.560 --> 00:10:31.820
But now we have a
simple thing, r dr,

00:10:31.820 --> 00:10:33.570
which we know how to integrate.

00:10:33.570 --> 00:10:37.010
And then here, dr is--

00:10:37.010 --> 00:10:38.480
sorry, dP is given.

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:41.510
So we have an assumption
about what that rate is right

00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:47.680
so dP is taken out as
well as a constant.

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:52.960
And we, again, integrate
from 0 through L. And sorry,

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:54.140
and theta is also constant.

00:10:54.140 --> 00:10:54.640
Right?

00:10:54.640 --> 00:10:56.600
So we can take that out.

00:10:56.600 --> 00:11:00.230
And we have r squared dr.

00:11:00.230 --> 00:11:03.220
So now it looks a
lot simpler, and we

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:06.340
can do the simple integral.

00:11:06.340 --> 00:11:06.840
Right?

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:09.030
Integral of r dr is
r squared over 2.

00:11:09.030 --> 00:11:11.640
Integral of r squared
is r cubed over 3.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:13.860
So we can substitute that in.

00:11:16.450 --> 00:11:25.520
So we have Pc theta
over 2 times r squared--

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:28.310
and r squared goes from 0 to L--

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:37.540
minus dP theta over 3.

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:46.420
And we have r cubed
going from 0 to L.

00:11:46.420 --> 00:11:52.750
And now we just simplify things,
and we compute the going from 0

00:11:52.750 --> 00:11:54.460
to L on both sides.

00:11:54.460 --> 00:12:04.940
So we are left with Pc theta
over 2 times L squared.

00:12:04.940 --> 00:12:08.510
When these ranges are 0, this
term is 0, and that term is 0.

00:12:08.510 --> 00:12:12.160
So all that matters is plugging
in-- substituting L for r.

00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:12.890
Right?

00:12:12.890 --> 00:12:15.510
And the terms of minus 0 are 0.

00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:17.710
So we don't need to write them.

00:12:21.730 --> 00:12:27.010
dP theta over 3 L cubed--

00:12:33.702 --> 00:12:40.340
and just collecting terms,
the ones that look similar--

00:12:40.340 --> 00:12:47.983
Pc/2 minus dP L/3.

00:12:51.240 --> 00:12:54.420
OK, so this is the
population in the corridor.

00:12:59.550 --> 00:13:02.560
And it's a function of the
properties of the corridor.

00:13:02.560 --> 00:13:03.060
Right?

00:13:03.060 --> 00:13:06.700
So if the corridor
is longer, then we

00:13:06.700 --> 00:13:09.160
have a higher population.

00:13:09.160 --> 00:13:11.885
If the angle of the corridor
gets wider [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:11.885 --> 00:13:13.010
population in the corridor.

00:13:13.010 --> 00:13:14.470
That also makes sense.

00:13:14.470 --> 00:13:17.905
And then it also depends on the
population of the city center--

00:13:17.905 --> 00:13:20.830
the higher it is, the bigger
the population in the center.

00:13:20.830 --> 00:13:24.760
And it depends on the rate at
which the population decreases

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:26.320
from the center--

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:28.117
the smaller the
rate of decrease,

00:13:28.117 --> 00:13:29.200
the larger the population.

00:13:29.200 --> 00:13:30.075
Right?

00:13:30.075 --> 00:13:30.950
Does that make sense?

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:39.000
OK, and now, in terms
of peak passenger flow,

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:44.880
we can look at units, but we'll
have to add some assumptions.

00:13:44.880 --> 00:13:49.252
So actually, I
think, at this point,

00:13:49.252 --> 00:13:50.960
I can probably stop
the math on the board

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:52.480
and just go straight to it.

00:13:52.480 --> 00:13:56.435
So this is the modeling part.

00:13:56.435 --> 00:13:58.810
And now we're just going to
make some assumptions about--

00:13:58.810 --> 00:14:02.200
given that the population in the
corridor and some assumptions

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:04.390
about what L and
theta and Pc and dP

00:14:04.390 --> 00:14:10.150
are and some assumptions about
the share of those people that

00:14:10.150 --> 00:14:15.750
would take transit, we'll look
at what the peak passenger

00:14:15.750 --> 00:14:16.360
flow is.

00:14:16.360 --> 00:14:18.090
So let's go straight to it.

00:14:18.090 --> 00:14:19.960
Here we have the
variables that I

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:22.890
defined on the board and
some additional ones.

00:14:22.890 --> 00:14:24.640
We have t, c, m, and p.

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:25.140
Right?

00:14:25.140 --> 00:14:28.422
So t is the number of one-way
trips per person per day.

00:14:28.422 --> 00:14:29.880
We're going to have
to assume this.

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:35.960
c is the share of trips
that are inbound to the CBD,

00:14:35.960 --> 00:14:37.440
as opposed to going outbound.

00:14:37.440 --> 00:14:37.940
Right?

00:14:37.940 --> 00:14:43.260
So it's what
percentage go inbound.

00:14:43.260 --> 00:14:46.260
m is the transit market
share for CBD-bound trips.

00:14:46.260 --> 00:14:49.230
So some people will take
cars or other modes.

00:14:49.230 --> 00:14:52.620
And we want to have some
assumption about what

00:14:52.620 --> 00:14:57.330
percent of people that
are going into the CBD

00:14:57.330 --> 00:15:00.840
will take transit, as
opposed to other modes.

00:15:00.840 --> 00:15:01.890
So that's m.

00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:05.130
And p is the share of CBD-bound
transit trips in the peak hour.

00:15:05.130 --> 00:15:06.720
So we want the peak hour flow.

00:15:06.720 --> 00:15:09.754
And maybe we don't
want the whole day.

00:15:09.754 --> 00:15:10.920
We just want peak hour flow.

00:15:10.920 --> 00:15:12.940
So there's going to be
some percentage of that.

00:15:12.940 --> 00:15:17.520
So here you have
the same equations

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:19.200
that I have on the board.

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:22.740
And the peak
passenger flow is what

00:15:22.740 --> 00:15:26.100
we have there, which is the
population in the corridor

00:15:26.100 --> 00:15:28.320
multiplied by our four
assumptions, our four

00:15:28.320 --> 00:15:30.600
factors that are
going to convert

00:15:30.600 --> 00:15:32.550
the population in
the whole corridor

00:15:32.550 --> 00:15:37.110
to what percent of people are
going to go into the CBD taking

00:15:37.110 --> 00:15:38.250
transit.

00:15:38.250 --> 00:15:42.090
Again, this is a very
simple, theoretical exercise,

00:15:42.090 --> 00:15:44.040
but it could be
useful at some point.

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:49.610
And we'll just plug
in for two examples.

00:15:49.610 --> 00:15:51.500
We have two scenarios
here-- one where

00:15:51.500 --> 00:15:54.830
the population density in the
CBD is 10,000 and another one

00:15:54.830 --> 00:15:56.240
where it's 20,000.

00:15:56.240 --> 00:16:00.290
For reference, in New York
City, the population density

00:16:00.290 --> 00:16:03.500
is about 28,000.

00:16:03.500 --> 00:16:08.840
So these are not as high
as those very dense cities.

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:11.334
AUDIENCE: But like what
is 10,000 [INAUDIBLE]??

00:16:11.334 --> 00:16:13.500
PROFESSOR: Depends how--
again, it's the same thing.

00:16:13.500 --> 00:16:15.900
Like it depends how
far you go and what

00:16:15.900 --> 00:16:17.040
you define as the center.

00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:20.220
But here are some numbers.

00:16:20.220 --> 00:16:21.420
This could be some city.

00:16:21.420 --> 00:16:21.920
Right?

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:27.270
These are typical
of some cities.

00:16:27.270 --> 00:16:30.330
So here we have some
decreases and the rate

00:16:30.330 --> 00:16:33.270
of decrease in the population
from the center going out.

00:16:33.270 --> 00:16:38.706
We're assuming a 40-degree
angle for the shape of this.

00:16:38.706 --> 00:16:40.080
If you have a
city, you know, you

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:42.690
have several lines
going in radially.

00:16:42.690 --> 00:16:45.600
This transit corridor serves
about a 40-degree angle.

00:16:45.600 --> 00:16:47.100
So--

00:16:47.100 --> 00:16:49.452
AUDIENCE: Is that--
that seems like a lot.

00:16:49.452 --> 00:16:50.410
PROFESSOR: It is a lot.

00:16:50.410 --> 00:16:51.620
AUDIENCE: Like maybe
a little too much.

00:16:51.620 --> 00:16:52.730
PROFESSOR: Well, it
depends how many--

00:16:52.730 --> 00:16:55.063
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] 40
degrees like in the inner part,

00:16:55.063 --> 00:16:57.495
but, you know, 40 degrees
you go [INAUDIBLE] miles out.

00:16:57.495 --> 00:17:00.317
Now you're already making
a [INAUDIBLE] arch.

00:17:00.317 --> 00:17:02.150
PROFESSOR: At the end,
it sounds like a lot,

00:17:02.150 --> 00:17:03.608
but, at the beginning,
not so much.

00:17:03.608 --> 00:17:09.569
If you think of a city,
you know, and you have--

00:17:09.569 --> 00:17:10.974
these are 90 degree angles.

00:17:10.974 --> 00:17:12.390
Right, and you add
two more lines.

00:17:12.390 --> 00:17:13.390
That's 45.

00:17:13.390 --> 00:17:17.089
So we're how many lines
would you have in a city?

00:17:17.089 --> 00:17:18.650
And it sort-- right?

00:17:18.650 --> 00:17:22.069
So it's not that unrealistic
to think of some line

00:17:22.069 --> 00:17:26.599
with a 40-degree angle coming
into the CBD from outside.

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:31.770
And we're assuming a
10-mile length and factors--

00:17:31.770 --> 00:17:37.730
so here we have 2.5,
0.2, 0.5, and 0.25.

00:17:37.730 --> 00:17:41.000
So that's the assumptions
for the different constants

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:45.590
to convert the whole population
into the number of people

00:17:45.590 --> 00:17:49.250
going inbound in the
morning rush taking transit.

00:17:49.250 --> 00:17:51.590
All right, so if
we plug that in,

00:17:51.590 --> 00:17:56.150
we get a required capacity of
10,000 in the first scenario

00:17:56.150 --> 00:17:57.860
and 30,000 in the
other scenario.

00:17:57.860 --> 00:18:00.180
And then from that,
one could say, well,

00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:04.250
can I have a bus system
serving 10,000 people per hour?

00:18:04.250 --> 00:18:07.820
Or can I have a bus
system or a rail system

00:18:07.820 --> 00:18:10.742
serving 30,000 people per hour.

00:18:10.742 --> 00:18:13.330
That's accommodating a
flow, which this is, again,

00:18:13.330 --> 00:18:14.930
a back-of-the-napkin
calculation,

00:18:14.930 --> 00:18:19.190
but it gives you an idea of,
based on the characteristics

00:18:19.190 --> 00:18:22.440
of some city, what
we would need.

00:18:22.440 --> 00:18:25.840
So let's look at some
theoretical capacities now.

00:18:25.840 --> 00:18:30.580
So in this slide, we
are looking at kind

00:18:30.580 --> 00:18:35.870
of high-end, upper bounds
almost on these modes.

00:18:35.870 --> 00:18:38.300
So for rail, let's
assume a very long train,

00:18:38.300 --> 00:18:42.830
which is 10 cars long, and it's
packed with 200 people per car.

00:18:42.830 --> 00:18:45.490
And it runs at a high
frequency, every two minutes.

00:18:45.490 --> 00:18:47.740
That gives you 60,000
passengers per hour.

00:18:47.740 --> 00:18:50.830
So that's about as
much as a metro system

00:18:50.830 --> 00:18:55.870
can provide in terms of
capacity or a line, metro

00:18:55.870 --> 00:18:57.732
line, a single metro line.

00:18:57.732 --> 00:19:03.110
If we look at bus, so a
full bus, 70 passengers,

00:19:03.110 --> 00:19:04.420
that's quite packed.

00:19:04.420 --> 00:19:06.340
You could run, if you
have multiple bays,

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:07.930
you could run
30-second headways.

00:19:07.930 --> 00:19:11.950
So if you see, BRT corridors
have capacity to do that.

00:19:11.950 --> 00:19:15.340
Obviously, if they are queuing
up to serve a single stop,

00:19:15.340 --> 00:19:16.720
that could not happen.

00:19:16.720 --> 00:19:19.660
But if you have multiple
bays, that can happen.

00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:24.320
So based on that assumption,
you can get 8,400.

00:19:24.320 --> 00:19:26.920
All right, so that's
pushing the limits of bus.

00:19:26.920 --> 00:19:30.380
BRT-- BRT vehicles are longer.

00:19:30.380 --> 00:19:32.140
So you might fit
200 people in one

00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:35.890
of these double-articulated
vehicles.

00:19:35.890 --> 00:19:41.230
You might have even 20-second
headways with good facilities.

00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:44.050
That gives you 36,000
passengers per hour, again,

00:19:44.050 --> 00:19:45.730
pushing the limits here.

00:19:45.730 --> 00:19:48.460
Light rail, I have
to say that I'm

00:19:48.460 --> 00:19:50.426
assuming a two-car
train here, but we

00:19:50.426 --> 00:19:51.550
could have three-car train.

00:19:51.550 --> 00:19:53.008
So maybe I'm not
pushing the limits

00:19:53.008 --> 00:19:54.890
as much on light rail here.

00:19:54.890 --> 00:19:58.120
But based on a two-car train
assumption and 150 passengers

00:19:58.120 --> 00:20:01.420
per car, which is quite a
bit for a light rail car,

00:20:01.420 --> 00:20:03.940
and assuming one-minute
headway, that's

00:20:03.940 --> 00:20:05.320
18,000 passengers per hour.

00:20:05.320 --> 00:20:05.820
Right?

00:20:05.820 --> 00:20:07.430
So you can compare these.

00:20:07.430 --> 00:20:09.520
And again, these are all
kind of upper bounds.

00:20:09.520 --> 00:20:12.580
Maybe light rail can be
pushed a little higher.

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:16.960
But it gives you an idea of what
the theoretical capacities are.

00:20:16.960 --> 00:20:19.300
So now we have this
back-of-the-envelope

00:20:19.300 --> 00:20:20.710
calculation--

00:20:20.710 --> 00:20:22.780
10,000, 30,000.

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:25.930
And what would we
need for 10,000?

00:20:25.930 --> 00:20:30.760
Could we serve that
10,000 demand with a bus?

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:32.530
Probably not.

00:20:32.530 --> 00:20:34.960
Do we need rail,
BRT, or light rail?

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:35.620
Probably so.

00:20:35.620 --> 00:20:37.110
So it gives you an idea.

00:20:37.110 --> 00:20:39.070
And if it's the 30,000
example, well, it

00:20:39.070 --> 00:20:41.500
looks like we're
going to need rail.

00:20:41.500 --> 00:20:42.400
Right?

00:20:42.400 --> 00:20:45.366
Because BRT is kind of--

00:20:45.366 --> 00:20:46.990
you're getting to
the high end of that.

00:20:46.990 --> 00:20:50.280
So we're probably going
to need rail for that.

00:20:50.280 --> 00:20:52.980
OK, and now let's look at
what happens here in Boston.

00:20:52.980 --> 00:20:56.070
So it's much lower
here, nowhere near

00:20:56.070 --> 00:20:58.400
the theoretical
capacities, right,

00:20:58.400 --> 00:20:59.850
that we're talking about.

00:20:59.850 --> 00:21:02.790
These are peak-hour volumes
for the different lines.

00:21:02.790 --> 00:21:06.570
So if we look at the Red Line,
which is the most crowded line,

00:21:06.570 --> 00:21:09.160
in the Cambridge section,
which is the most crowded,

00:21:09.160 --> 00:21:11.920
especially between Central
Square and MIT-- actually,

00:21:11.920 --> 00:21:14.970
that's the highest
point on the system--

00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:19.740
we have almost 10,000 people
per hour, passengers per hour.

00:21:19.740 --> 00:21:22.963
AUDIENCE: We saw in
a different course--

00:21:22.963 --> 00:21:24.504
one of the people
from the T who came

00:21:24.504 --> 00:21:26.700
who was a graduate
of the MST program

00:21:26.700 --> 00:21:28.457
showed slightly higher
numbers than that.

00:21:28.457 --> 00:21:30.665
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so these
numbers are a little dated.

00:21:30.665 --> 00:21:33.690
And it depends on how
you define the peak hour.

00:21:33.690 --> 00:21:37.020
And you know, I could show
you the peak 15 minutes,

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:39.100
and that would be higher
than this, for example.

00:21:39.100 --> 00:21:42.170
So if you look at the peak--

00:21:42.170 --> 00:21:45.610
yeah, like the peak of the peak,
it's even higher than this.

00:21:45.610 --> 00:21:49.316
But it still is the case that
these are not approaching

00:21:49.316 --> 00:21:50.440
the theoretical capacities.

00:21:50.440 --> 00:21:52.445
And that's because we
don't have, you know,

00:21:52.445 --> 00:21:57.030
two-minute headways and
10-car trains or yeah.

00:21:57.030 --> 00:22:01.270
So right, so the Orange Line,
we have two sections here,

00:22:01.270 --> 00:22:04.920
the north and the
southwest, similar numbers.

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:06.395
Blue Line is slightly lower.

00:22:06.395 --> 00:22:11.300
On the Green Line, the branches
do about, you know, 1,800,

00:22:11.300 --> 00:22:13.050
less than 2,000 each.

00:22:13.050 --> 00:22:17.570
So we're looking at a much
lower number than the light rail

00:22:17.570 --> 00:22:20.620
theoretical capacity.

00:22:20.620 --> 00:22:23.510
And in the central subway
where all these branches merge,

00:22:23.510 --> 00:22:27.955
we get a much higher demand,
but it's still lower.

00:22:27.955 --> 00:22:30.080
Again, these vehicles are
not running every minute.

00:22:30.080 --> 00:22:35.300
And in some cases, they
are, but not consistently.

00:22:35.300 --> 00:22:40.114
And we don't fill
all the vehicles,

00:22:40.114 --> 00:22:42.740
you know, to crush
load for a whole hour.

00:22:42.740 --> 00:22:43.820
Right?

00:22:43.820 --> 00:22:46.520
So we're not getting
that capacity.

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:48.300
We're not delivering
that capacity.

00:22:48.300 --> 00:22:49.841
So it gives you an
idea where we are.

00:22:49.841 --> 00:22:52.650
If you've used the
system here in Boston,

00:22:52.650 --> 00:22:56.520
you might relate taking
the train at peak hour

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:58.800
to what these numbers
look like and think

00:22:58.800 --> 00:23:02.910
about what it would take to
increase capacity in terms

00:23:02.910 --> 00:23:07.140
of more cars or a
higher demand spread

00:23:07.140 --> 00:23:10.650
over a longer peak
and things like that.

00:23:10.650 --> 00:23:14.250
OK, now let's look at
worldwide urban rail systems.

00:23:14.250 --> 00:23:17.960
This is metro, and I have
grouped it by continent.

00:23:17.960 --> 00:23:22.560
And it starts sort
of before the 1900s.

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:29.730
And you can see the earlier
systems started in Europe--

00:23:29.730 --> 00:23:32.590
London, Budapest.

00:23:32.590 --> 00:23:33.870
Right?

00:23:33.870 --> 00:23:36.540
And then North America
followed closely after that.

00:23:36.540 --> 00:23:40.200
Boston takes the prize
for the first subway.

00:23:40.200 --> 00:23:41.300
That's the Green Line.

00:23:41.300 --> 00:23:43.230
And even though we call
it light rail here,

00:23:43.230 --> 00:23:46.480
we're calling it
metro in the slide.

00:23:46.480 --> 00:23:49.320
So we have a few starts
in North America,

00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:53.362
and it sort of falls
flat in 1920s and 1930s.

00:23:53.362 --> 00:23:54.570
And then it takes off again--

00:23:54.570 --> 00:23:56.300
1960s all the up.

00:23:56.300 --> 00:23:57.870
It keeps increasing.

00:23:57.870 --> 00:23:59.470
Asia was a little
slower to start,

00:23:59.470 --> 00:24:01.980
but it's going up really fast.

00:24:01.980 --> 00:24:04.230
China is building
a lot of metro.

00:24:04.230 --> 00:24:08.160
Africa, I think it has
two systems right now.

00:24:08.160 --> 00:24:10.860
And there are no systems that
I am aware of in Australia,

00:24:10.860 --> 00:24:13.050
but they are building
one that should

00:24:13.050 --> 00:24:16.080
start before the end of
this decade in Sydney.

00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:18.960
So they're going
forward with that.

00:24:18.960 --> 00:24:21.240
So this is, you know--

00:24:21.240 --> 00:24:23.040
you can see that
we're building metro

00:24:23.040 --> 00:24:24.616
and that it goes
together with what

00:24:24.616 --> 00:24:25.740
we said on the first class.

00:24:25.740 --> 00:24:27.130
Population is increasing.

00:24:27.130 --> 00:24:29.100
And especially urban
population is increasing.

00:24:29.100 --> 00:24:32.610
People are moving away from
rural areas into cities.

00:24:32.610 --> 00:24:36.290
The required capacities to
have agglomeration benefits

00:24:36.290 --> 00:24:40.230
and avoid traffic and
air pollution problems

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:45.390
is requiring higher density,
higher flow systems like metro.

00:24:45.390 --> 00:24:46.290
Questions?

00:24:46.290 --> 00:24:48.615
AUDIENCE: So you've got
