00:26:35.510 --> 00:26:36.140
and then down.

00:26:36.140 --> 00:26:37.580
And these are
based on statistics

00:26:37.580 --> 00:26:40.850
of currently-operating systems
that started at some point

00:26:40.850 --> 00:26:41.670
in the past.

00:26:41.670 --> 00:26:42.170
Right?

00:26:42.170 --> 00:26:44.400
So that's a good point.

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:46.320
Thank you for bringing that up.

00:26:46.320 --> 00:26:51.980
And we see here Africa,
Oceania, so Australia--

00:26:51.980 --> 00:26:56.000
and let's see.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:59.000
Yeah, Africa, South
America, and Australia

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:00.140
don't have many systems.

00:27:00.140 --> 00:27:00.640
Right?

00:27:00.640 --> 00:27:05.990
So mainly, we have
[INAUDIBLE] in Asia,

00:27:05.990 --> 00:27:08.400
and increasingly so
in North America,

00:27:08.400 --> 00:27:11.060
but not at the same
level as in Asia.

00:27:11.060 --> 00:27:15.360
Obviously, that has to do
with the size of the cities

00:27:15.360 --> 00:27:17.370
and the number of
large cities as well.

00:27:17.370 --> 00:27:24.210
So OK, capital costs, so
these are based, once more,

00:27:24.210 --> 00:27:28.570
on the NTD numbers, the
National Transit Database.

00:27:28.570 --> 00:27:33.560
These are 2013 numbers that were
published in the 2015 APTA Fact

00:27:33.560 --> 00:27:34.100
Book.

00:27:34.100 --> 00:27:37.260
And you can download
that on Stellar

00:27:37.260 --> 00:27:39.600
if you want to look
at these in detail.

00:27:39.600 --> 00:27:43.740
So $18.2 billion was
spent in capital costs,

00:27:43.740 --> 00:27:46.600
and we're going to look at
how that cost was distributed.

00:27:46.600 --> 00:27:49.320
So if we look at by type,
about a quarter of that

00:27:49.320 --> 00:27:53.430
was spent on purchasing vehicles
or rehauling old vehicles

00:27:53.430 --> 00:27:56.010
for their midlife repair.

00:27:56.010 --> 00:28:00.480
And about 60% was spent on
infrastructure and facilities.

00:28:00.480 --> 00:28:05.130
All right, so that could include
new rail lines or extensions,

00:28:05.130 --> 00:28:11.880
repairs of those, bus stops,
maintenance facilities, right,

00:28:11.880 --> 00:28:13.590
offices, things like that.

00:28:13.590 --> 00:28:17.940
And then about 15%, 16%
was spent on other things.

00:28:17.940 --> 00:28:23.470
Those other things could be
AFC systems, other things that

00:28:23.470 --> 00:28:24.860
are not vehicles or facilities.

00:28:24.860 --> 00:28:25.360
Right?

00:28:25.360 --> 00:28:28.540
So OK, by mode,
about a quarter was

00:28:28.540 --> 00:28:32.980
spent on bus projects, about
35% on heavy rail projects,

00:28:32.980 --> 00:28:36.310
and then less, a little less,
on commuter rail and light rail,

00:28:36.310 --> 00:28:38.500
and then 5% in other modes.

00:28:38.500 --> 00:28:41.870
And that's mostly paratransit
or demand responsive, as they

00:28:41.870 --> 00:28:44.530
[INAUDIBLE] APTA Fact Book.

00:28:44.530 --> 00:28:51.150
So it gives you an idea of
how the US, on any given year,

00:28:51.150 --> 00:28:54.990
distributes the
capital expenditures.

00:28:54.990 --> 00:28:59.210
You might think that,
from year to year,

00:28:59.210 --> 00:29:03.290
these costs vary a lot because
capital investments are

00:29:03.290 --> 00:29:03.870
very lumpy.

00:29:03.870 --> 00:29:04.370
Right?

00:29:04.370 --> 00:29:05.630
You don't have them,
and, all of a sudden,

00:29:05.630 --> 00:29:07.509
you invest a lot of
money into a system.

00:29:07.509 --> 00:29:09.050
But because there
are so many cities,

00:29:09.050 --> 00:29:12.110
they don't actually
vary that much.

00:29:12.110 --> 00:29:14.840
And the other reason
that doesn't happen

00:29:14.840 --> 00:29:19.030
is because a lot of the
expenditures are gradual.

00:29:19.030 --> 00:29:21.880
So it takes several
years to build new lines.

00:29:21.880 --> 00:29:25.360
So they are distributed
over several years,

00:29:25.360 --> 00:29:26.740
instead of all at once.

00:29:29.610 --> 00:29:32.160
And here we have the
breakdown by mode and type

00:29:32.160 --> 00:29:32.940
at the same time.

00:29:32.940 --> 00:29:38.070
So about-- the key takeaway
here is so $4.5 billion

00:29:38.070 --> 00:29:40.980
was spent on bus projects.

00:29:40.980 --> 00:29:43.950
And about half of that was
on vehicles and about half

00:29:43.950 --> 00:29:47.310
was on facilities, the
repair facilities, bus stops,

00:29:47.310 --> 00:29:49.590
things of that nature.

00:29:49.590 --> 00:29:53.610
When we look at rail, the
percent spent on vehicles

00:29:53.610 --> 00:29:54.400
is much lower.

00:29:54.400 --> 00:29:58.360
It's about 10% to 20%,
7% to 20% in this case,

00:29:58.360 --> 00:30:00.720
depending on the
specific rail mode.

00:30:00.720 --> 00:30:04.842
And closer to 90% is spent on
infrastructure and facilities.

00:30:04.842 --> 00:30:05.550
That makes sense.

00:30:05.550 --> 00:30:06.050
Right?

00:30:06.050 --> 00:30:07.350
You have to lay--

00:30:07.350 --> 00:30:08.700
you have to sort of put rail.

00:30:08.700 --> 00:30:11.490
You have to build stations.

00:30:11.490 --> 00:30:13.510
The maintenance yards
are more expensive.

00:30:13.510 --> 00:30:16.320
So these are bigger projects.

00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:21.010
To the extent that the
right of way is a subway,

00:30:21.010 --> 00:30:22.030
then you have to dig.

00:30:22.030 --> 00:30:24.900
And so it's very expensive.

00:30:24.900 --> 00:30:29.160
And here you have the total
expenditure, capital cost

00:30:29.160 --> 00:30:29.810
by mode.

00:30:29.810 --> 00:30:34.170
And so 4.5 on bus, 6.2 on
heavy rail, 3 on commuter rail,

00:30:34.170 --> 00:30:35.250
3.5 on light rail.

00:30:38.016 --> 00:30:40.640
OK, and now focusing on
infrastructure costs,

00:30:40.640 --> 00:30:44.715
so what drives the
infrastructure costs?

00:30:44.715 --> 00:30:46.340
First, the type of
construction, right,

00:30:46.340 --> 00:30:49.190
so if we look at
heavy rail, you could

00:30:49.190 --> 00:30:52.430
build at grade, so
leveled on the street

00:30:52.430 --> 00:30:55.430
or on sort of new
lands that you don't

00:30:55.430 --> 00:30:58.100
have to acquire from anyone.

00:30:58.100 --> 00:30:59.600
That's the least expensive.

00:30:59.600 --> 00:31:00.736
Then you move to elevated.

00:31:00.736 --> 00:31:02.360
If you have to go
over streets, and you

00:31:02.360 --> 00:31:07.100
have an elevated section, that's
the second most expensive.

00:31:07.100 --> 00:31:09.370
And then subway tends to
be the most expensive.

00:31:09.370 --> 00:31:11.390
And there are two
ways of doing that.

00:31:11.390 --> 00:31:12.450
There's cut and cover.

00:31:12.450 --> 00:31:13.700
So that's a shallow tunnel.

00:31:13.700 --> 00:31:14.900
You dig a hole.

00:31:14.900 --> 00:31:18.140
You put the rail lines, and then
you build a roof on top of it,

00:31:18.140 --> 00:31:20.150
and cars drive over it.

00:31:20.150 --> 00:31:21.470
That's shallow tunnel.

00:31:21.470 --> 00:31:24.200
And then there's deep tunnel,
which is the most expensive.

00:31:24.200 --> 00:31:26.840
That tends to be with a
tunnel boring machine.

00:31:26.840 --> 00:31:31.650
So you get these huge
machines that drill the hole.

00:31:31.650 --> 00:31:35.300
They're very fun to
learn about and look it.

00:31:35.300 --> 00:31:37.880
I encourage you to YouTube them.

00:31:37.880 --> 00:31:41.450
And they are usually
built for the project.

00:31:41.450 --> 00:31:43.730
And when they
finish digging, they

00:31:43.730 --> 00:31:45.350
are sort of taken off course.

00:31:45.350 --> 00:31:49.340
And they sort of remain
interred at the level.

00:31:49.340 --> 00:31:52.790
So they're kind of used
once, and there you go.

00:31:52.790 --> 00:31:57.860
So London has used a lot of
these for their very deep Tube.

00:31:57.860 --> 00:32:00.563
And yeah, you should
look at these on YouTube.

00:32:00.563 --> 00:32:02.354
AUDIENCE: In New York,
it's kind of common.

00:32:02.354 --> 00:32:04.074
Right?

00:32:04.074 --> 00:32:04.990
PROFESSOR: Yeah, yeah.

00:32:04.990 --> 00:32:06.240
AUDIENCE: It basically
goes along the avenues.

00:32:06.240 --> 00:32:08.131
PROFESSOR: Yeah, so in
London, we have both.

00:32:08.131 --> 00:32:08.630
Right?

00:32:08.630 --> 00:32:11.294
So the earlier lines like
the Central Line and the--

00:32:11.294 --> 00:32:12.960
AUDIENCE: Yeah, the
Circle and District.

00:32:12.960 --> 00:32:13.940
PROFESSOR: The Circle
and District Lines

00:32:13.940 --> 00:32:15.770
are definitely cut and cover.

00:32:15.770 --> 00:32:17.731
And then the Silver
Line is very deep.

00:32:17.731 --> 00:32:18.230
Right?

00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:20.530
And so that's a
tunnel boring machine.

00:32:20.530 --> 00:32:22.530
AUDIENCE: Can you give a
sense of the difference

00:32:22.530 --> 00:32:27.536
between let's say at grade,
elevated, and shallow and deep?

00:32:27.536 --> 00:32:29.660
PROFESSOR: Maybe I should
have shown some pictures.

00:32:29.660 --> 00:32:32.075
But at grade is just
at street level.

00:32:32.075 --> 00:32:34.357
AUDIENCE: No, I know, but
like the difference in cost.

00:32:34.357 --> 00:32:34.940
PROFESSOR: Oh.

00:32:34.940 --> 00:32:36.260
AUDIENCE: Like cost per mile.

00:32:36.260 --> 00:32:37.550
PROFESSOR: Oh, I'll
give some examples

00:32:37.550 --> 00:32:38.570
in the next few slides.

00:32:38.570 --> 00:32:40.370
Yeah, that's a good segue.

00:32:40.370 --> 00:32:43.320
So the other key factors are
land acquisition and clearance.

00:32:43.320 --> 00:32:45.140
So if you're
building a new line,

00:32:45.140 --> 00:32:48.830
and you have to use eminent
domain and sort of buy property

00:32:48.830 --> 00:32:51.710
from people who own them,
who own that property,

00:32:51.710 --> 00:32:55.010
to build your new line,
that costs some money.

00:32:55.010 --> 00:32:58.670
Also, the number, size,
complexity, and length

00:32:58.670 --> 00:32:59.840
of the stations--

00:32:59.840 --> 00:33:03.170
so station design is
a key component here

00:33:03.170 --> 00:33:04.730
and the complexity
of the system.

00:33:04.730 --> 00:33:05.930
Is this an independent line?

00:33:05.930 --> 00:33:08.250
Or are there many
points of transfer?

00:33:08.250 --> 00:33:11.990
And how do you coordinate that?

00:33:11.990 --> 00:33:14.750
During construction, do
you have to keep operating

00:33:14.750 --> 00:33:15.950
some parts of the line?

00:33:15.950 --> 00:33:17.630
How do you manage that?

00:33:17.630 --> 00:33:21.470
So if you look at, for
example, the repair

00:33:21.470 --> 00:33:25.190
of the bridge, the Longfellow
Bridge here in Boston,

00:33:25.190 --> 00:33:28.760
we wanted to do that with rail,
for the most part, running.

00:33:28.760 --> 00:33:31.760
So that has increased the
costs of that project.

00:33:31.760 --> 00:33:34.010
You couldn't just take the
bridge down and rebuild it.

00:33:34.010 --> 00:33:37.490
And we wouldn't have the
Red Line for a long time.

00:33:40.850 --> 00:33:44.162
OK, so here are
some typical costs.

00:33:44.162 --> 00:33:45.370
Here are some, four examples.

00:33:45.370 --> 00:33:46.390
Right?

00:33:46.390 --> 00:33:47.980
And they vary a lot,
but it gives you

00:33:47.980 --> 00:33:49.730
some idea of the
magnitude of these costs.

00:33:49.730 --> 00:33:54.060
So Tren Urbano was one of
the most recent systems.

00:33:54.060 --> 00:33:56.960
It was built in 2002 in
San Juan, Puerto Rico.

00:33:56.960 --> 00:34:00.130
And it 50% at grade,
about 40% elevated,

00:34:00.130 --> 00:34:03.400
and 10% subway, just a small
section that was subway.

00:34:03.400 --> 00:34:06.620
It cost about $2
billion to build.

00:34:06.620 --> 00:34:08.830
And if you divide that by
the length of the corridor,

00:34:08.830 --> 00:34:13.850
it comes out to $118
million per kilometer.

00:34:13.850 --> 00:34:14.350
Right?

00:34:14.350 --> 00:34:16.960
So it gives you an
idea of what it takes.

00:34:16.960 --> 00:34:20.350
The MBTA Red Line in
1984, it was extended

00:34:20.350 --> 00:34:23.830
to Alewife from Harvard.

00:34:23.830 --> 00:34:27.520
And that was 5 kilometer
extension, four stations.

00:34:27.520 --> 00:34:28.989
It was all subway.

00:34:28.989 --> 00:34:33.639
So it cost $0.6 billion
of $600 million.

00:34:33.639 --> 00:34:37.710
And that comes up to $120
million per kilometer.

00:34:37.710 --> 00:34:41.199
All these figures are in the
dollar numbers of the year

00:34:41.199 --> 00:34:45.159
that they were built. They're
not adjusted for inflation.

00:34:45.159 --> 00:34:47.340
Then we have the
Los Angeles MTA.

00:34:47.340 --> 00:34:50.730
That was a new system
started in the late 1980s.

00:34:50.730 --> 00:34:53.580
It was all subway, 7 kilometers.

00:34:53.580 --> 00:34:57.870
$1.2 billion comes
out to $180 million

00:34:57.870 --> 00:35:02.220
per kilometer, so same
range, right, or similar.

00:35:02.220 --> 00:35:06.070
I mean, obviously, from 120
to 180, it's 60 million.

00:35:06.070 --> 00:35:08.490
That's a lot of money,
but same ballpark,

00:35:08.490 --> 00:35:10.280
same order of magnitude.

00:35:10.280 --> 00:35:14.160
WMATA was cheaper on
a unit cost basis.

00:35:14.160 --> 00:35:19.580
It was built over several
decades, multiple phases, 100

00:35:19.580 --> 00:35:23.700
kilometers, so lots of stations,
lots of distance covered.

00:35:23.700 --> 00:35:26.340
It's a mix of subway,
elevated, and at grade.

00:35:26.340 --> 00:35:31.950
And it cost $6.4 billion, and
that comes out to $60 million

00:35:31.950 --> 00:35:32.930
per kilometer.

00:35:32.930 --> 00:35:34.301
So yeah.

